    {
      "id": "mnswhrt6",
      "questionNumber": 5,
      "questionText": "<p>$$ \\text { The following structures are } $$</p><img alt=\"JEE Main 2026 (Online) 4th April Evening Shift Chemistry - Basics of Organic Chemistry Question 6 English\" src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/6y3zli1mnujmk7u/62a47119-e4e1-4a55-ae17-293e47f35d00/a5ab23a0-35c2-11f1-bedb-8be0f67d0034/file-6y3zli1mnujmk7v.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/6y3zli1mnujmk7u/62a47119-e4e1-4a55-ae17-293e47f35d00/a5ab23a0-35c2-11f1-bedb-8be0f67d0034/file-6y3zli1mnujmk7v.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\">",
      "options": [
        "<p>enantiomers.</p>\n",
        "<p>identical molecules.</p>\n",
        "<p>diastereomers.</p>\n",
        "<p>meso compounds.</p>"
      ],
      "correctOption": 1,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "isomerism",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>The given compound does not have a chiral centre because the carbon shown is not attached to four different groups.</p>\n<p>Here, $-\\mathrm{CH}_3$ and $-\\mathrm{Me}$ represent the same substituent (both are methyl groups). So, two of the four bonds are to identical groups.</p>\n<p>Therefore, this carbon cannot be a chiral centre, and the structures cannot be enantiomers, diastereomers, or meso forms.</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
